<Author>Candy16
<Content>If you love nature and dont expect luxury this place is great. I really have mixed feelings about this Parador, the location is very nice, you are surounded by nature and peace. However the hotel could improve certain aspects such as the beds and the room conditions.We arrived early, around 10 am, and were checked in at once, we stood in room #9, which was really modest, a simple bathroom, a few drawers, and a TV with cable,however it was spacious, the rooms dont have windows but wooden shutters without screens which we loved because you could open them and enjoy the view of the mountains and feel the mountain breeze. No need to turn on the A/C. We had problems the first night, the bed!!!! It was in really bad shape!!! You could feel the holes and the springs because it was really worn out. No matter how many sheets or blankets it was still horrible. In the middle of the night my husband went up to the desk to inquire about changing rooms, it was then when we realized that after 10pm all the employees leave, they lock up the office,the little lobby and leave the guests on their own, in the office the post a number to call in case of emergency, but thats about it.Next morning we asked to be changed. we were moved at once to room #5 and given a discount for the night. The room was perfect, it was right next to the beautifull antique lobby, it had an antique decor with stone floors and furniture, the room even had a great spacious wooden balcony looking over the pool and the mountains, the balcony has a table, 2 chairs and a little hammock, there was even a bird nest of this native bird that sang every morning. The food in Gripinas is good, nothing gourmet, very local, we had the chicken asopao which is a hearthy soup,delicious!! We also tried the rice and beans served with skirt steak, very good. The breakfast are wonderful, they make a great coffee and the a delicious farina. You must try the eggs with local ham, great!!! All the food is well proportioned, and the staff is really accomodating.Our experience with the hoseback ride was not so good, we went to the desk asking for info about hoseback rides, the girl told us he would sent someone to the room with the info, 10 minutes later a man called To帽ito showed up offering us the tour. My husband talked to him for a while and was quite puzzeld when he was asked how much each of us weighed. In short ,offered us a 2 hour tour for 50 dollars, which we considered ok. He picked us up at the front of the hotel in a shabby jeep which felt it would fall appart any minute, we drove for maybe 10 minutes and arrived at a wooden shack wich he claimed was his home. From there we would start the ride into a coffee plantation. What we saw next was shameful, 2 rather small horses in bad shape were being prep for the ride. They looked kind of skinny and tired, no wonder they asked our weight, these horses would not been able to carry a common overweight person.It was also strange that this man who was our tour gide had two 14 year olds tending the horses and made them come on the tour with us by foot. At first I was skeptical but they all insisted that it was ok and that they did this tour everyday. We started the ride going up a really steep hill, the horses breathing became so heavy that for a moment I thought they would colapse, the two boys went up by foot, while all the time the guide To帽ito followed us in his jeep. We were led into this beautifu plantation, here we were explained about the the history of jayuya, the local traditions and the process of puertorican coffee harvest we were also taken to a lovely stream where we rested for a while and headed for an anciet indian burial ground. The place was lovely but I kept being distracted beause my horse was famished and kept on going off course to eat the grass. One of the boys (Miguel) was really sweet and asked me a lot of questions, I asked if he gets payed for what he does, he said no, he just did it for fun. On the way down the horses were so tired I decided to give it a break so I decended on foot, I even got a taste of some bananas right off the tree, and some water directly from the stream, it was totally safe. Once we got back to the hotel I commented to the desk about the condition of the tour, their response was just quick reply oh well, we really dont own the tour, we just recomend them. So much for safety and quality concern.Besides that our stay was ok, I would return for a weekend, maybe just for a night but not more than 2. If you have kids, skip this place, there is no activities at all execpt for the pool which is small and the water is always cold because it comes directly from the mountains, no nightlife whatsoever, and town is really boring.You need a car to go to all the fun places like the Indian ceremonial park which was great. If you are looking for peace and quiet, love nature and are not looking for any luxuries this place might be good for you. 
