<Author>TejasJuez
<Content>Mixed Feelings I delayed writing this review to see how I felt upon reflecting on our experience. Let me first say that my comments about the room all relate to room number 10, the room we stayed in. I am convinced that there are better rooms at this property.The location: This hotel is truly in the middle of nowhere. We had no cell phone service at all, and the craziness of the cities of P.R. is nowhere to be found. For those of you reading this, I think the best way to get to Jayuya and Hacienda Gripinas is through Ponce, even if you are in San Juan. It was recommended to us by several Puerto Rican friends not to drive along the northern coast and then into the mountains, but to cut across the island on the tollway to Ponce and then drive up. We did that, and based on what others have said, I think we spent less time on the winding narrow mountain roads. Let me echo other reviews: DO NOT ATTEMPT TO FIND THIS PROPERTY AT NIGHT. The people: For the most part, the people who work at H.G. are some of the friendliest and most helpful we have encountered on our travels anywhere. And we have traveled many places. They helped us with bags, took us to our room, etc. I wish they had provided us with more information about coffee plantations in the area. See below for our one unpleasant people-related experience.The food: The food is included here, and it is decent. It was certainly not the best food we had in P.R., but also not the worst. The service at dinner and breakfast was very friendly. Breakfast was very good. I recommend the omelettes.The pools: Just so that it's clear, the pools are fed by water running off the mountain. It is rainwater and cold. For those who are paranoid about swimming in mountain streams, these pools might not be for you. I don't think they are chlorinated. But we loved them, even though we had blue lips by the time we got out of the water.The room: Our room was not so nice. There were several problems. The water in the bathroom dripped constantly, and the bathroom smelled terribly of mildew and mold. The ventilation from the bathroom went into the open air hallway through a small window. The small window had no screen, and with the moisture in the bathroom, our room was a party for the mosquitos. So, upon our arrival, I killed every mosquito I could find, and I shut the bathroom door so that no more mosquitos could find their way into our sleeping quarters. To me, the lack of screens at this place is a real health hazard with the mosquitos. The window in our room looked onto the back of the kitchen stairs. The window was a long row of wooden shutters, again without screens, but they closed effectively to keep the mosquitos out. We just couldn't open them without risking flying visitors. Above the shutters was colored glass block. There were no curtains over the glass block, and there were about 6 120-watt bulbs in the hallway. All night long it was bright enough to read in our room because of the lack of curtains. We did not get much sleep due to the light. Because we did not sleep we decided to cancel our second night's stay and leave. That is where our problems began.Checkout: Early in the morning, we told them we did not want to stay a second night, and asked if we could have the second night refunded. We were told we'd have to wait for a manager. So we waited for an hour or so, enjoyed our breakfast, and then talked to a manager. The manager was polite and concerned about why we were leaving early. We told her about the light issue in the room, and she apologized. We asked her if she could refund us one night's charge, and she agreed to do it. However, she did not do it, and despite our emails, we have not received a refund for the second night, as of today. We are now disputing the charge with our credit card company, and we'll see if that will help.Conclusion: I would book this property for one night only. They will likely have a room available if you want to stay a second night. Ponce and its major hotels are not far if you can't stay a second night. Don't stay in room 10. If you have room in your suitcase, pack a roll of duct tape to cover the glass block and block out the light if you get stuck in room 10. Bring a swimsuit and enjoy yourself. If you love coffee like we do, spend a little time before your trip planning a route to visit different growers. I do wish the hotel had more information about different coffee plantations in the area. They only told us about one, but there are so many. 
