<Author>HuaMulan
<Content>A Treat of a Mountain Retreat After the bustle of San Juan and its over-priced lodging options, my husband and I rented a car to see the heart of Puerto Rico. Nestled amid the highest mountains on the island and at the end of several twisting, narrow, cliff-hanging roads, we came to rest at Hacienda Gripinas outside the village of Jayuya. The hacienda was originally a prosperous coffee plantation and has retained the flavor and atmosphere of another era. We had a choice of two rooms and opted for one on the main floor, just off the dining area, a reading lounge, and main balcony. Our room opened onto its own balcony that overlooked a swimming pool with views of the mountains. Had the hacienda been busy, the location of this room next to public areas would have been less than ideal, but at most, there were two other couples that weekday night. Lulled by the wind and the sounds of coqui, we could easily pretend that we had this beautiful, quiet place all to ourselves. Our stay included both dinner and breakfast with many tasty menu options and ample portions. Miguel, our receptionist, host and waiter, was courteous and attentive - including finding an extra blanket for the cool mountain night. My only complaint was the erratic water temperature when I wanted a hot shower. It took a long long time running the water before it became hot and a short short time before it went cold again. At the mid-week price of $109 for room, dinner, and breakfast, Hacienda Gripinas is a budget traveler's dream. As a unique hotel with the character and charm of old Puerto Rico, it is everyone's dream. If we could have stayed longer, we would have, and if we have a chance to return, we will. 
