<Author>humanone
<Content>Hacienda Gripinas was a great experience Hacienda Gripinas is not a luxury hotel nor a resort, which is why it is so wonderful. One feels as if one were in the past (except for the ariconditioners) including the smaller rooms and simple furnishings of that time along with the multiple sitting rooms and public verandas.. And it is in the countryside (duh!) which includes bugs and a bit of mildew along with the incredible blossoming trees at your terrace, the charming coqui frog chirps, and the vistas. It is true that it is almost two hours from the caverns, but a look at a map will tell you that it is a winding mountain road that takes you there. Again, driving those roads were wonderful, with the towering clumps of wild giant bamboo along the way. If you are not interested in another culture and a different terrain, don't leave New York or wherever. And...the plaintain soup was the best soup I have ever had, with the Spanish omlette the next day excellent as well'; the rest of the food was Ok. $125 for two people to sleep and have dinner and breakfast seems totally fair to me. 
