<Content>A Walk in the Clouds For a getaway from the increasing urban development that's become characteristic of the Puerto Rican metropolitan area, this guesthouse is perfect. My girlfriend and I stayed overnight in room #5 and we loved the guesthouse, its setting, the openness of the guesthouse and the grounds. Our room was off of the main living room and had a semi-private balcony that overlooked the pool. Our bed and pillows were lousy, but the serenity of the mountains and singing Coqui frog more than made up for this. The ride to the town of Jayuya from the east (Cayey) is itself a breathtaking ride through winding roads with awesome vistas. The staff is friendly, courteous and attentive. There was no hot water, which was disappointing after our 4+ hour trek and given how cold it can get up in the mountains (relative to the lowlands, of course). If your getting in at night, bear in mind that getting to Gripi帽as is tricky and signage is non-existent. We had to stop to ask for directions several times once we got into the town of Jayuya. Dinner and breakfast were included with our stay as was a courtesy Pi帽a Colada (sans alcohol -- no liquor sold in Gripi帽as). The Creole Snapper left a lot to be desired and I've had better rice and beans all my life. Breakfast on the other hand, a Spanish Omelette, was much better. For all the rave reviews about the coffee, I found it mediocre. All in all, Hacienda Gripi帽a was a wonderful retreat from the metropolitan scene. 
